        Official Singles Chart on 11/12/2020

        11 December 2020 - 17 December 2020

        The Official Singles Chart Top 100 reflects the UK’s biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1. View the biggest songs of 2025.

        Personally I count them all as #2s, with digital re-issues (as opposed to a 26-year-old release getting to #1 'at last'). Of the 3 physical #2s above, all 3 digital re-issues are currently in their highest position with 3 of their traditional sales weeks to go (24th/31st/7th). One digital reissue has exceeded it's physical peak, one equalled and the other still below.

        Last Christmas now will always be the biggest selling #2 physical hit. If it gets to #1 and we combine the physical and digital issues, then we have a new best-selling #2 of all time. But which?

        Since digital issues came in, Christmas reissues have been becoming bigger and bigger hits year on year: More and more of the chart are Christmas reissues of previous physical hits, a few minor new hits (Kelly Clarkson / Ariana Grande / Sia) and Jess Glynne with a brand new one for this year!

        Of the old songs, they're usually in roughly the same order each year and reaching higher peaks with each successive year until the top of the chart is so near, they can't go any higher (The 3rd year running Fairytale has hit #4 and 4th year in the top 5).

        The reasons for this year are obvious (and it's started earlier this year too), but any insight why this is a trend for the whole of the previous decade and not just a blip year?

        Carry on at this rate, we'll have a top 10 comprising of only old Christmas songs by 2025!
